<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Jagasian]]></name></author>
<updated>2007-05-28T17:03:19-07:00</updated>
<published>2007-05-28T17:03:19-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3387&amp;p=24511#p24511</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3387&amp;p=24511#p24511"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[proper archival format discussion on bannister.org]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3387&amp;p=24511#p24511"><![CDATA[
So all we need is a comprehensive enumeration of every board type for the NES and Famicom, along with enough documentation for enough board type, so that each board type can be properly emulated.  Once that is done, every NES and Famicom _cart_ needs to be redumped to a "cart" file that contains the board type and ROM dumps.  Simple enough in theory, but to make it a reality would require a massive amount of effort.  Also, new board types would require new board type IDs.  So a "whole cart" HDL based format would be the most open-ended, as it wouldn't require allocating new board type IDs.  It would also be self documenting.<br /><br />Using a "whole cart" format as opposed to a ROM-only format, a single game could have multiple different game files, as the same game may have different board types as well as different ROM versions.  Right now, a single game only has multiple game files, when the ROMs differ.  So yeah, there is definitely a loss of information, when the board type makes a difference, just as different ROM versions can make a difference.<br /><br />Isn't it inconsistent to care when a ROM differs, but not care when the board type differs?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=94">Jagasian</a> — Mon May 28, 2007 5:03 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
